There is a bug in retrieving array elements in GWT array reflection code.
Current code looks like this - 

```
package com.badlogic.gdx.utils.reflect;
public final class ArrayReflection {
...
    /** Returns the value of the indexed component in the supplied array. */
    static public Object get (Object array, int index) {
        ReflectionCache.instance.getArrayElement(ReflectionCache.getType(array.getClass()), array, index);
        return array;
    }
...
```

Returning the array itself is a bug. It should be 

```
package com.badlogic.gdx.utils.reflect;
public final class ArrayReflection {
...
    /** Returns the value of the indexed component in the supplied array. */
    static public Object get (Object array, int index) {
        return ReflectionCache.instance.getArrayElement(ReflectionCache.getType(array.getClass()), array, index);
    }
...
```

Tried to calculate the distance with the implemented GJK in Bullet Physics. But there are two Problem: 
1. I can't put the btVoronoiSimplexSolver as SWIGTYPE_p_btSimplexSolverInterface.
   (typdef should solve this)
2. btPointCollector doesn't extend the btDiscreteCollisionDetectorInterface::Result.
   (http://bulletphysics.org/Bullet/BulletFull/structbtPointCollector.html)

Code should look like this (couldn't test):

```
    public float calculateDistance() {
        btVoronoiSimplexSolver solverV = new btVoronoiSimplexSolver();
        btSimplexSolverInterface solver = new btSimplexSolverInterface(solverV);
        btConvexPenetrationDepthSolver epa = new btGjkEpaPenetrationDepthSolver();
        Vector3 sepAxes = new Vector3(0f, 0.059727669f, 0.29259586f);

        btConvexShape closestShape1 = new btBoxShape(new Vector3(1, 1, 1));
        btConvexShape closestShape2 = new btBoxShape(new Vector3(1, 1, 1));

        btGjkPairDetector pairD = new btGjkPairDetector(closestShape1, closestShape2, solver, epa);
        pairD.setCachedSeperatingAxis(new Vector3(0.00000000f,0.059727669f,0.29259586f));
        btPointCollector output = new btPointCollector();
        ClosestPointInput input = new ClosestPointInput();
        btIDebugDraw debugDraw = new btIDebugDraw();
        debugDraw.setDebugMode(0);

        input.setTransformA(new btTransform());
        btTransform t = new btTransform();
        t.setOrigin(new btVector3(4, 4, 4));
        input.setTransformB(t);

        pairD.getClosestPoints(input, output, debugDraw);

        if(output.getHasResult()) {
            return output.getDistance();
        }
        return -1000;
    }

       public class btSimplexSolverInterface extends
            SWIGTYPE_p_btSimplexSolverInterface {
        btVoronoiSimplexSolver solver;

        public btSimplexSolverInterface(btVoronoiSimplexSolver solver) {
            super(btVoronoiSimplexSolver.getCPtr(solver), false);
            this.solver = solver;
        }


        public void dispose() {
            if (solver != null)
                solver.dispose();
            solver = null;
        }
    }

```

The Application interface has a setLogLevel but no getLogLevel. It would be useful to have this method to be able to enclose expensive debug code inside a test, i.e. 

if (Gdx.app.getLogLevel() >= Application.LOG_DEBUG) {
  // Some expensive debug diagnostics here
}
